# Observations
# ------------
#
# - there is a dintinction between a pin (on the outside of the package) and a
#   pad (internally on the chip). Pad are bonded to pins when the chip is
#   packaged, and sometimes, more than one pad is bonded to the same pin.  Pads
#   are a property of the series, and pins are a property of the part.  The GPIO
#   peripheral configures pads, not pins, but if two or more pads are bonded to
#   the same pin, at most one of them can be configured as output.
#
# - a pin can be used simultanuously for multiple input signals but not for
#   multiple output signals (typically wired nor functionality)
#
# - the same signal may require different pad configurations depending on
#   peripheral settings, so let's configure pads based on peripheral settings.
#   In some cases, there are options; these should be part of the peripheral
#   settings.
#
# - some microcontrollers can select signals per pad, others have peripheral
#   settings that select pads for multiple signals at the same time
#
# - to keep configuration simple,  let's assign at most one signal per pin
#
# - if multiple signal-to-pad assignments are controlled by the same setting,
#   then selecting one of them also selects the others; so, if one of the other
#   affected pads already has a different assignment controlled by a different
#   setting, we need to warn the user (conflict)
#
# - we want to provide signal-to-pad mapping both on the pad and on the
#   peripheral, regardless of whether the mapping is per pad or shared; the same
#   is true for other pad settings, such as PU/PD/PP/OD or speed
#
# - some peripherals do not require all signals to be mapped to peripherals;
#   in that case, the peripheral user interface should have tick marks to enable
#   optional signals
#
# - core config data should contain the necessary information to configure the
#   user interface as well as to generate code from user input
#
# User interface configuration needs
# ----------------------------------
#
# - generic package information, such as the number of pns and the layout
#
# - series name
#
# - part names with corresponding package and pin number to pad name mapping
#
# - pad capabilities;  often,  many pads have the same capabilities,  so we
#   may want to define a pad type,  and then define capabilities per type
#
# - settings for signal-to-pad mapping, per pad and/or per peripheral
#
# A pin can either be unassigned or claimed by a single peripheral. GPIO is
# considered a peripheral.  The user interface should allow only one peripheral
# to claim a given pin. If more than one peripheral claims the same pin,
# behavior is undefined.  It is therefore not important what happens when
# multiple peripherals claim the same pin. The core config data does not need to
# contain that information.
#
# Pad to signal mapping links a pad to a signal controlled by an enable bit
# and a selection bit field. Both bit fields are optional. The enable bit can be
# virtual: an input does not need to be disabled, as long as it is ignored by
# the firmware.
#
# We can try to insert the description of mapping to an existing description of
# a pad, peripheral or signal, to avoid duplication and to group related
# information.  However, achieving this requires more than one format for
# pad-to-signal mapping, and duplication cannot always be avoided.
#
#  - If a bit field maps multiple signals of a peripheral together, it is most
#    conveniently added to the peripheral description. We can use a single
#    construct for the bit field, requiring duplication of pad and signal
#    names. This is not possible when there is no bit field involved in the
#    mapping (fixed mapping).
#
#  - If a bit field maps a single pad, we can add it to the pad description.
#    This avoids duplication of the pad name, at the cost of duplicating the
#    names of the bit field and the signal.
#
#  - If a bit field maps only a single signal, we can add it to the signal
#    description, duplicating the pad names. This can also work when no bit
#    field is involved (fixed mapping).
#
# A basic pad-to-signal map in peripheral context has the following format:
#
# "peripherals" {
#     "<peripheral-name>": {
#         "map": {
#             "bit-field-1": {
#                 "signal-1": [ "pad-1", "pad-2", ... ],
#                 "signal-2": [ "pad-3", "pad-4", ... ],
#                 ...
#             },
#             "bit-field-2": {
#                 "signal-3": [ "pad-1", "pad-2", ... ],
#                 "signal-4": [ "pad-3", "pad-4", ... ],
#                 ...
#             }
#         },
#         ...
#     }
# }
#
# This resembles the tables given in some reference manuals, e.g. CH32V003RM
# page 55 to 56.
#
# The same bit field or pad name can occur in multiple map statements, but each
# signal name can occur only once in a map; in other words, each signal has
# only one bit field that can be used to configure it.
#
# Each list must contain 2^n pad names, where n is the width of the bit field.
# The signal is assigned to the i'th pad, where i is the value of the bit
# field.  If a signal is not assigned to any pad for a given value of the bit
# field, replace the corresponding list entry by null.
#
# We also allow a different format instead of a list:
#
#            "signal-name-1": {
#                "bit-pattern-1": "pad-1",
#                "bit-pattern-2:  "pad-2",
#            }, ...
#
# In this case, each bit pattern is a string consisting of n characters '0', '1'
# or 'x', where n is again the width of the bit field. The pad is assigned to
# the signal if the binary value of the bit field matches the bit pattern. An
# 'x' matches either '0' or '1', and a '0' or '1' match themselves. If more than
# one bit pattern matches a value, the one with the smallest number of 'x's
# wins. A draw is an error. No match means no pad assignment.
#
# For a fixed mapping, we can skip the bit field level,  and replace the pad list
# by a single pad name:
#
# "peripherals" {
#     "<peripheral-name>": {
#         "map": {
#             "signal-1": "pad-1",
#             "signal-2": "pad-2",
#             ...
#         },
#         ...
#     }
# }
#
# A map for a single signal can be added to the signal description:
#
# "peripherals" {
#     "<peripheral-name>": {
#         "signals": {
#             "signal-name-1": {
#                 ...
#                 "map": { "bit-field-1": [ "pad-1", "pad-2", ... ] }
#             },
#             "signal-name-2": {
#                 ...
#                 "map": "pad-3"
#             },
#             ...
#         }
#         ...
#     }
# }
#
# A map for a pad can look as follows:
#
# "pads": {
#     "pad-name-1": {
#         "map": { "bit-field-1": [ "signal-1", "signal-2", ... ] },
#         ...
#     },
#     "pad-name-2": {
#         "map": "signal-1",
#         ...
#     },
#     ...
# }
#
# Alternatively, we can collect the mapping for all pads in one statement, to
# more closely resemble the typical table in the documentation:
#
# "map": {
#     "bit-field-1": { "pad-1": [ "signal-1", "signal-2", ... ]}, 
#     "bit-field-2": { "pad-2", [ "signal-3", "signal-4", ... ]}, 
#     ...
# }
#
# Compared to the map statements within peripherals, this reverses the role of
# pad and signal. The signal list must have 2^n entries for a bit field with
# width n.  Signals can be null for undefined map entries. We can also allow
# bit pattern notation, avoiding the need for null entries:
#
# "map": {
#     "bit-field-1": { "pad-1": {
#             "bit-pattern-1: "signal-1",
#             "bit-pattern-2: "signal-2",
#             ...
#     }},
#     ...
# }
#
# For GPIO, the signal name is equal to the pad name, and no remapping is
# possible. Signal names already need to be listed, so that we can add
# capabilities and options; so listing the signals again in a map seems
# unnecessary. We can make signal-name-equals-pad-name the default.
#
# If signal names are not globally unique, they can be prefixed by their
# peripheral names. For example, if both TIM1 and TIM2 have a CH1 signal, we
# can refer to them as TIM1.CH1 and TIM2.CH1, respectively. Some data sheets and
# other documents use '_' instead of '.' as a separator between peripheral name
# and signal name; we can allow that as long as the result is unambiguous
# (e.g. peripheral names never have '_'), but use '.' on output for clarity.
# Inside peripheral descriptions, we can default the peripheral name prefix,
# requiring an explicit prefix to refer to signals of other peripherals.
#
# A similar approach is used for bit field names and register names: if a bit
# field name is not globally unique, it can be prefixed by the register name,
# with a '.' separator or optionally an '_'.
#
# Conflict detection and handling; enable and optional flags
# ----------------------------------------------------------
#
# Signals can be optional; we can add `"optional": true` for optional
# signals. Optional output signals need an enable bit, or a disable bit
# field and value, to avoid conflicts. It is important to know which input
# signals of a peripheral are optional: if only optional signals have no pad
# mapping for a given part, the peripheral can still be used for that part, but
# if required signals have no pad mapping, the peripheral is unusable.
#
# We can use `"disable": "bit-field"` (1 bit wide) or `"disable": [ "bit-field",
# "value" ]` (can be more than one bit wide, and specific value disables) on an
# optional signal. In that case, it is automatically also optional; there is
# no need to add the "optional" attribute explicitly.  We can also use
# `"enable": "bit-field"` if the bit field must be 1 to enable the signal.
# `"enable": "bit-field"` is equivalent to `"disable": [ "bit-field", "0" ]`.
# `"disable": "bit-field"` is equivalent to `"disable": [ "bit-field", "1" ]`.
#
# A conflict occurs when two or more peripherals claim the same pin. This can
# happen when the user changes a mapping bitfield, or enables a peripheral or
# peripheral signal. We can either resolve conflicts immediately, or list them
# (maybe by marking the conflicted pins). We can also show a subtle warning near
# the widgets or options that will cause a conflict when selected. And we can
# refuse to generate code until all conflicts are resolved.
#
# We need to be able to determine when a peripheral claims the pins to which its
# signals are mapped. In many cases, this corresponds to an enable bit for the
# peripheral and/or the signal, but this is not always true.
#
# For example, there is not necessarily an enable bit for a GPIO input: the
# decision to use a GPIO pad as digital input does not imply any specific
# configuration. From the user point of view, it requires that no other
# peripheral uses that pad, so many other configuration bits are involved. There
# might also be more than one bit involved. For example, for the CH32V003
# series, the decision to use a pad as GPIO output requires the MODE bits to be
# set to 01, 10 or 11, depending on the desired speed. Mode is 00 for an input.
#
# So, in a way, the choice to use a pad for a specific signal is a virtual
# decision, especially for an input pad. The same pad can technically be used as
# input by many peripheral; there is no configuration conflict, the conflict is
# purely conceptual, or due to hardware external to the chip.
#
# We don't want to bother the user with the details of registers and bit fields.
# Let's provide a conceptual 'enable' flag for each signal.
#
# Do we need a similar flag per peripheral? We can try to derive that
# automatically: a peripheral is enabled as soon as one of its signals is
# enabled. The issue with that approach is that for some peripherals, it is not
# possible to disable all signals individually, so enabling one signal may
# automatically also enable other signals. So yes, we do need an 'enable' flag
# per peripheral as well.
#
# It is possible that some peripherals cannot be disabled, or that some
# signals cannot be disabled individually, so we need to inform the user
# interface whether a given peripheral or signal can be disabled. Let's
# provide an 'optional' flag that is true for peripherals and signals that can
# be disabled.
#
# A GPIO peripheral is typically not only responsible for digital I/O, but also
# for pad configuration with options like speed and PU/PD (for inputs) and PP/OD
# (for outputs). In this case, the GPIO peripheral needs to be enabled to
# configure its pads, even if they are only used by other peripherals. This
# might not be obvious to the user, so we should not provide an 'enable' flag
# for such a GPIO peripheral (iow, the peripheral should not be optional); the
# responsibility to enable a GPIO peripheral should be taken by code generation.
#
# We can also provide a similar 'enable' flag for clocks; but not all clocks can
# be disabled, so we also need to provide the 'optional' flag for clocks.
#
# For code generation, we do need to know which bit fields to set to enable a
# peripheral signal. We allow an 'enable' json tag for each clock, peripheral
# and signal.  This is a logical expression in terms of bit fields. The
# default value is '1'.  TODO
#
#
# Generic options
# ---------------
#
# We can generate generic user interface widgets for most RW fields.  The SVD
# provides these fields, but unfortunately, it does not provide a description of
# the values. We can add this to the json, by almost literally copying the
# register definitions in the reference manual.  For example:
#
#      "options": {
#        "PLS": {
#          "desc": "PVD voltage monitoring threshold setting. See the 
#                   Electrical Characteristics section of the datasheet for
#                   detailed instructions.",
#          "values": {
#            "000": "2.85V rising edge/2.7V falling edge.",
#            "001": "3.05V rising edge/2.9V falling edge.",
#            "010": "3.3V rising edge/3.15V falling edge.",
#            "011": "3.5V rising edge/3.3V falling edge.",
#            "100": "3.7V rising edge/3.5V falling edge.",
#            "101": "3.9V rising edge/3.7V falling edge.",
#            "110": "4.1V rising edge/3.9V falling edge.",
#            "111": "4.4V rising edge/4.2V falling edge."
#          }
#        },
#        ...
#      }
#
# The reset value is assumed to be zero, unless explicitly added. Values can be
# integers, or quoted binary strings, or hexadecimal strings starting with 0x
# (?).
#
# Not all writable fields should generate user interface widgets; for example,
# clock settings and remapping are handled differently. Also, for some well know
# peripherals, we may want to offer a custom made widget.
#
#

Take 1
------

Peripherals have an 'enable' expression. The peripheral's registers can only be
accessed when 'enable' is true. It does not otherwise affect the peripheral's
functioning.

Signals also have an 'enable' expression. Signals only access a pin if they
are mapped to a pin and their enable expression is true. It is not necessary

The default enable expression is '1' (true) for both peripherals and signals.
This means that there are two ways to disable a signal: make it's enable
expression false, or map it to null.


Take 2
======

Peripherals
-----------

Peripherals of the current part are the peripherals of the series for which all
required signals can be mapped to a pin of the part (at the same time -
although this last constraint is not checked yet). Peripherals can be added to
and removed from a configuration (by the user, using the UI).

Signals and pin claims
------------------------

Peripheral settings determine which signals of a peripheral are enabled
through the signal's "enable" expression. The expression may refer to SFR bit
field values, which reflect the peripheral's settings. When a peripheral is
added, its enabled signals claim their pins.

However, it is not always possible to determine an "enable" expression for all
signals. For example, whether a GPIO pin is used as input is not reflected by
any SFR bit field, so cannot be captured in an expression. It can only be
determined by looking at the firmware.

A better approach might be to turn this around: the user selects which pins he
wants to use, and this forces the corresponding enable expressions to
true. Depending on the expression, it may or may not be possible to do this
automatically. If there is only one way to do it, we can do it
automatically. Otherwise, the user will have to do it by configuring the
peripheral's settings.

The advantage of this approach is that it is easy to determine which signals
claim a pin, so also easy to detect conflicts.

Conflicts
---------

When an enabled signal of an added peripheral is mapped to a pin, it claims
that pin. When a signal claims a pin, it forces one of the signal's modes
onto the pad. If there is more than one, we choose the first one, and the user
interface must offer a way to select another one.

If more than one signal claims a pin, a conflict occurs. The configuration
will report conflicts using callbacks. It will not automatically resolve them.
No code can be generated while a conflict exists.

There are some UI design decisions to be made here.  

1. Should the list show only enabled signals of peripherals that were added to
the configuration, or also other signals?

2. If it also shows other signals, should selecting them automatically add the
   peripheral and/or enable the signal?

3. If multiple signal-to-pad mappings are linked due to a shared remap
   setting, should we still allow selecting the mapping on the pin, or
   single-pin settings on the peripheral?

4. If a requested signal-to-pin mapping can be realized in several ways,
   which way should be chosen? Offer the user a choice between all possibilities,
   only non-conflicting possibilities,  or just choose one?

These are decisions that can be made in the UI. The model and configuration
provide all the necessary information:
- which peripheral a signal belongs to (Signal.peripheral),
- which peripherals have been added to the configuration (Config.has_peripheral
  and Config.peripherals),
- which signals a given pin can potentially provide (Part.signals_for_pin),
- (TODO) which signals are enabled (Config.is_signal_enabled),
- (TODO) what is the list of available mapping options for a given signal or
  pin,  what are the additional mappings implied by each option, and which
  of them conflict with existing mappings?







The core config and model software will not automatically add a peripheral or
enable or enable a signal when it is mapped.

Automatic mapping
-----------------

We will attempt to implement automatic mapping and automatic conflict resolution
later.

Automatic mapping will require a way to assign signals to a group of
equivalent signals; examples are GPIO and ADC. Signals in a group must have
the same settings and modes. The user should be able to set the required number
of signals from each group, give them names and change their settings
including pad settings.

With or without automatic mapping, it should remain possible to manually assign
signals to pins, including signals belonging to a group. These pre-mapped
signals should not be considered for automatic mapping.




A signal can be assigned to a group.






I need some help with terminology, or maybe to clarify a concept. I will try to
explain below. Please excuse me if the explanation is not 100% clear yet; this
is my attempt to clarify it.

In the description of an MCU for the config tool (json file), I am adding an
expression describing when a signal is actually "used" by its peripheral. The
idea is that you cannot assign two or more such signals to the same pin; that
would be a conflict.

In my terminology, a signal is "used" (by its peripheral) when it is either an
output, or if the input value of the signal directly affects the operation of
the peripheral.

A GPIO configured as input does not "use" its pin; the value on the pins does
not affect the behavior of the GPIO peripheral, and if you don't read it from
firmware, it has no effect. Such a pin does not conflict with any other use of
the pin, so the pin can be safely reused for another function.

If you configure a USART for hardware flow control, the CTS (Clear To Send)
signal is an input, but it is used internally to control whether bytes in the
output buffer are transmitted or not, so as long as hardware flow control is
enabled, this signal cannot be reused for another signal.

To reliably detect conflicts, I need to know the difference between these two
situations, so I need an expression - in terms of SFR bit fields - that tells me
whether a peripheral actually uses a given signal, or not.

Also, if a signal is "used" by its peripheral (in its current configuration), we
should give a warning if it is not mapped to any pin at all.

Initially, I used "enable" instead of "use" in the json file, but that doesn't
feel right: a GPIO input pin is not "disabled", you can still read it from
firmware. It is also still "used", from firmware, so "used" doesn't feel right
either.

Is there an example other than a GPIO input where an input is only used when it
is read by firmware? Would a MISO or RX signal qualify? Maybe, but there is an
easy work-around: we can allow the user to "disable" MISO or RX, and this can be
implemented by not using an alternate function mode on the corresponding pin.

In general we can allow the user to disable any input signal. Whether an output
signal is enabled purely depends on SFR bitfield settings; this will be
represented by an "enable" expression. 

Together, this provides enough information to detect conflicts (two enabled
signals assigned to the same pin) and missing assignments (an enabled signal not
mapped to any pin), as well as implement automatic pin assignment.

In most situations, we can the chip 

To detect conflict detection, missing pinFor GPIO inputs, this
has no effect

There is however one exception, one situation that we cannot handle

If we want to be able to verify that every "used" signal is enabled, we will
need the "used" expression


CH32V003
--------

TIM2.ETR and TIM2.CH1 are always assigned to the same pad.

The mode for TIM2.ETR is FI.  The mode for TIM2.CH1 can be FI or PP-AF.

How can we know that this is OK, even if both ETR and CH1 are enabled? Maybe
even if CH1 is in PP-AF mode?  Accept this is there is a mapping that assigns
both to the same pad?  That doesn't work when mapping is done per pad, but that
is irrelevant: with that style, you cannot assign two signals to the same
pad. So yes, that is an option. But is it actually OK?



Package description
-------------------

If we define our own format: 

For packages with pins at the edges, we would need:

- a basic rectangle width x height

- number of pins on each side (can be zero)

- a marker for the corner where the numbering starts (like a small circle, or a
  cut-off corner, or ???)

Based on that, we can position the pins on the edges (spread them evenly) and
add a label centered in the rectangle.
